{"履修期": "春学期後半", "主な教授言語": "英語", "授業目的": "Global Supply Chain Management:This course addresses what I call a \"boundary issue\" of multinational business management, focusing on the interfaces among product/service development, procurement, and marketing activities on a global basis. Since the 1990s, increased outsourcing of manufacturing activities and services has become a prominent part of the restructuring of firms’ supply chains. Academics and consultancy firms have largely supported the view of outsourcing as one of the key drivers of superior performance. As we are now increasingly discovering, the drawbacks of outsourcing, or put differently, the advantages of vertical integration, have been underestimated or even neglected. In this course, we explore a more balanced view of global supply chain management (sourcing strategy) and the performance of the firm. For managers we provide indications of how they can achieve the required balance.&nbsp;", "到達目標": "The fundamental premise underlying global supply chain management is the boundary-spanning nature of the topic, encompassing all aspects of product development to product delivery mechanisms, involving R&amp;D, manufacturing, and marketing on a global basis. Global supply chain management must be market-driven, and calls for not just cost reduction in the movement of materials, components, and products but also achieving customer satisfaction. The key challenges for business organizations include developing a shared vision throughout the organization about 1) how cost-efficiently the market should be served and 2) how effectively customer satisfaction should be accomplished. Pursuing the minimization of total cost in global supply chain does not necessarily correspond to the maximization of customer satisfaction. Indeed, achieving customer satisfaction can be costly. At the end of the course, you will learn to acquire a strategic thought process to accomplish this balancing act in delivering the product to the customer. You will also learn the changing nature of global competition and the importance of the simultaneous pursuit of economies of scale and cultural sensitivities in global supply chain management.&nbsp;", "特記事項": "", "関連科目": "International Business, International Marketing", "授業の概要・背景": "", "授業方法": "Face to face class format.The course is taught, using a combination of lectures, case analysis, and class discussion. The textbook will give you a broad picture of what global supply chain management is and how it affects corporate performance.&nbsp;To enhance your grasp and management of various problems associated with global supply chain, you are required to work in a group on both Assignments (A) Case Analysis and (B) Case-Writing Group Project. Each group will be made up of a number of students and will work as a unit for all group assignments throughout the semester. A comprehensive exam is also scheduled as Assignment (C) to assess your understanding of the class material.", "トピック": {"第1回": ["<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-top:3.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:3.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:12.0pt;mso-line-height-rule:exactly;\"><strong><span times=\"times\" new=\"new\" roman\",serif;\"=\"roman',serif;'\" style=\"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:;\">Global Supply Chain Management as an Academic Subject (1)</span></strong></p>\n\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-top:3.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:3.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:12.0pt;mso-line-height-rule:exactly;\"><strong><span times=\"times\" new=\"new\" roman\",serif;\"=\"roman',serif;'\" style=\"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:;\">Classic Macro Controversy: Deindustrialization?</span></strong></p>", "<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin:3pt 0in 3pt 16.95pt;font-size:11.0224px;text-indent:-0.25in;line-height:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Wingdings;font-size:11pt;\">§<span times=\"times\" new=\"new\" roman\";\"=\"roman';'\" style=\"font-variant-numeric:normal;font-variant-east-as